                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d72">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/5752: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName type="from"
                            >Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-01-16T09:00:00+08:00"
                            >January 16, 1933—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 16—12:53 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>52. Following from American Consul General at Mukden: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“January 15, 10 a.m. Although the concentration of Japanese troops along
                            Jehol border was denied by official spokesman here yesterday, it has
                            been learned from a reliable source that the Fourth Division was moving
                            southward from North Manchuria via Taonan. Indications are that
                            preparations for Jehol drive are being hastened and that it will
                            probably begin early in February.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
